<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-12</title>

<p>This week's strongest papers share a single impulse: they take scaffolding that robot-learning systems usually keep outside the model — memory, geometry, data curation — and move it inside the latent reasoning stream. LaMem-VLA treats episodic history as ordinary VLA tokens; RynnWorld-4D turns a 2D video diffusion backbone into a synchronized RGB-depth-flow predictor whose internal latents drive a closed-loop dexterous policy; SIEVE selects training data not by trajectory similarity but by reusable primitive composition. All three are buildable ideas, and all three raise the same follow-up question: once the scaffolding is internal, what new failure modes appear?</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> LaMem-VLA is the clearest conceptual move. It reframes robotic memory from "retrieval fed to the policy head" to "tokens attending inside the VLA sequence," and the ablations isolate exactly where the gain comes from.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Memory as native latent context</h1>

<p>Long-horizon manipulation only looks Markovian if you are willing to cheat. In practice, success depends on what happened ten seconds ago: whether the lid was already grasped, which side of the bowl is facing up, whether the previous subgoal completed. The usual fixes — expanding the context window or retrieving from an external memory bank — keep history at arm's length. Two papers this week try to dissolve that boundary.</p>

