<hr/>

<h2>LaMem-VLA: Dual Latent Memory in Vision-Language-Action Models for Robotic Manipulation</h2>

<p>Qu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.07608">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.07608">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/quhongyu/LaMem-VLA">Code</a></p>

<p>LaMem-VLA's central claim is that memory for robot control should not live in a side module; it should be tokens in the same continuous embedding space where the VLA already perceives, reasons, and forms action intent. The paper builds a four-stage loop — curator, seeker, condenser, weaver — around a 7B Prismatic VLM backbone and a diffusion action expert.</p>

<p>At each timestep the curator writes two vaults. A short-term vault stores compressed visual tokens from the current frame as key/value units; a long-term vault stores the previous action-query hidden states. When a vault exceeds capacity <latex>L</latex>, the most redundant adjacent pair (highest key cosine similarity) is merged by averaging. The seeker builds a context-aware query from the current visual and instruction tokens, mean-pools it, and retrieves the top-<latex>K</latex> units from both vaults. The condenser squeezes that retrieved evidence into a fixed number of latent memory tokens, <latex>L_s</latex> short-term and <latex>L_l</latex> long-term. Finally the weaver prepends them to the VLM input:</p>

<p><latex>\mathbf{S}_t = [\mathbf{M}^{\text{short}} + \mathbf{1}_{L_s}\mathbf{b}_s^\top ; \mathbf{M}^{\text{long}} + \mathbf{1}_{L_l}\mathbf{b}_l^\top ; \mathbf{X}_t ; \mathbf{I} ; \mathbf{Q}^{\text{action}}]</latex></p>

<p>The source embeddings <latex>\mathbf{b}_s, \mathbf{b}_l</latex> are learned, and the memory tokens attend to, and are attended by, the current observation, language, and action queries. Because the action-query outputs are therefore memory-grounded, the downstream diffusion expert receives a different conditioning vector than any policy-side memory bank can provide.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:lamem:overview]]</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="The four-stage LaMem loop (from the runnable probe in runs/2026-07-12-lamem-rynnworld-sieve/lamem-vla/code/lamem_probe.py)"><code># 1. Curator writes history into bounded vaults
short_vault.append(visual_compressor(X_t))  # key/value units
long_vault.append(H_action_prev)            # action hidden states
merge_most_redundant_adjacent_pair(vault)   # if |vault| &gt; L

# 2. Seeker retrieves context-relevant evidence
Q_t = query_builder([X_t; I; Q_init])[-K_q:]      # masked transformer
q_t = mean_pool(Q_t)
Z_short, Z_long = top_k_cosine(q_t, vaults)       # non-differentiable

# 3. Condenser reconstructs fixed-length memory tokens
M_short = memory_former([Q_t; Z_short; T_s])[-L_s:]
M_long  = memory_former([Q_t; Z_long;  T_l])[-L_l:]

# 4. Weaver injects memory as ordinary VLM tokens
S_t = concat([M_short + b_s, M_long + b_l, X_t, I, Q_action])
Z_action = vlm(S_t)[-N_a:]
action_chunk = diffusion_expert(Z_action)         # (B, 16, 7)</code></pre>

<p>The ablations are more informative than the headline numbers. Removing both memory streams drops SimplerEnv-Bridge to 57.3% and LIBERO-90 to 92.1%, essentially the memory-free CogACT baseline. Removing only short-term memory costs 8.3 points on SimplerEnv; removing only long-term costs 9.3 points. Policy-side conditioning — feeding retrieved evidence to the action head instead of weaving it into the VLM sequence — reaches 71.9% / 94.8%, below the full model's 73.9% / 97.0%. That gap is the empirical signature of the latent-native design.</p>

