<p>What I could not verify. The public repository is currently empty, and the downloaded arXiv source does not include the appendix, so the exact SE-bottleneck compressor, the masked-attention masks in the query builder and memory formers, and the bootstrap of an empty long-term vault are all underspecified. The probe I wrote fills these gaps with reasonable defaults, but a fully reproducible implementation will need the appendix or released code. The top-<latex>K</latex> retrieval is also non-differentiable, which means the model learns what to condense but not which vault unit to retrieve end-to-end. And every result is simulation-only; real-world validation is promised for a future version.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>From 2D video diffusion to 4D robot control</h1>

<p>Generative video models are good at looking plausible. They are much worse at being useful for manipulation, because pixels hide 3D structure, object scale flickers, and motion is only implicit. This week's world-model papers respond by making geometry and motion explicit without abandoning the scalability of video diffusion. The most ambitious of them, RynnWorld-4D, closes the loop all the way to a real bimanual dexterous robot.</p>

