<h2>RynnWorld-4D: 4D Embodied World Models for Robotic Manipulation</h2>

<p>Zhao et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.06559">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.06559">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/alibaba-damo-academy/RynnWorld-4D">Code</a></p>

<p>RynnWorld-4D's bet is that a lightweight projective 4D representation — synchronized RGB, depth, and optical flow (RGB-DF) — can inherit the generative prior of a large video diffusion model while exposing the geometry and motion that robot actions actually need. The model is built on Wan 2.2-TI2V-5B, a 30-layer latent video diffusion transformer, extended into three modality branches. Each branch keeps its own FFN and self-attention; text cross-attention K/V projections are shared because language is modality-agnostic.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:rynnworld:overview]]</p>

<p>The projective 4D reading is simple and explicit. Given camera intrinsics <latex>\mathbf{K}</latex>, depth <latex>D_t</latex>, and dense optical flow <latex>\mathbf{f}_{\text{opt}} = (\Delta u, \Delta v)</latex>, a pixel <latex>\mathbf{p}_t = (u, v, 1)</latex> lifts and tracks as:</p>

<p><latex>\mathbf{P}_t = D_t(u,v) \cdot \mathbf{K}^{-1}\mathbf{p}_t</latex></p>
<p><latex>\mathbf{P}_{t+1} = D_{t+1}(u+\Delta u, v+\Delta v) \cdot \mathbf{K}^{-1}(\mathbf{p}_t + [\Delta u, \Delta v, 0]^\top)</latex></p>
<p><latex>\mathbf{f}_{3D} = \mathbf{P}_{t+1} - \mathbf{P}_t</latex></p>

<p>That back-projection gives a per-point metric scene flow, which is what differentiates RynnWorld-4D from prior RGB-D-N work that relies on static geometry like normals. For a hand-over or lid-placement task, the relative 3D motion of two high-DoF end-effectors is exactly the signal that raw RGB struggles to encode.</p>

<p>Cross-modal consistency is enforced by Joint Cross-Modal Attention (JA) modules inserted every three layers. For each branch <latex>m</latex>, a single query attends to the concatenated keys and values of the other two branches, restricted to the same frame. The output projection is zero-initialized, but a scalar gate is initialized to 1 and passed through <latex>\tanh</latex>; this avoids the saddle point that would occur if both projection and gate started at zero, while still preserving the Stage-1 checkpoint as an initial residual.</p>

<p>The training recipe is three stages: independent branch adaptation, frozen-backbone joint-attention alignment, and full-parameter joint fine-tuning. A single shared Gaussian noise sample is used across all three branches so their denoising trajectories stay aligned. Branch dropout randomly corrupts depth or flow (but never RGB, the appearance anchor) to force the JA modules to reconstruct missing modalities.</p>

<p>For control, RynnWorld-4D-Policy does something clever: it reads the world model's internal latent state in a single forward pass rather than decoding video. The frozen world model is run at diffusion timestep <latex>t = 500</latex>, hidden states from block 15 of all three branches are concatenated into a 9216-dimensional conditioning vector, and a small perceiver-style Flow Former plus a 4-step flow-matching head outputs a chunk of 10 actions. The heavy backbone runs once per replan cycle (~1.1 s on an RTX 5090), giving an effective control frequency of ~9 Hz by executing the action chunk while the next plan computes in parallel.</p>

