<p>The internal ablations are the strongest evidence. Independent branches raise depth AbsRel from 0.310 to 0.737 and flow AEPE from 0.170 to 0.247. Skipping modality adaptation drops <latex>\delta_1</latex> from 0.610 to 0.479. Training only on task-specific robot data spikes AEPE from 0.170 to 0.729. Replacing the predictive encoder with a ResNet-18 drops Dual Picking success from 94.29% to 71.43%. These are clean, mechanistic demonstrations that the 4D latents matter.</p>

<p>What the code reveals. The public repository is Apache-2.0 and complete, but the released training scripts differ from the paper in two places. Stage-2/3 scripts use <code>--joint_unidirectional True</code>, meaning depth and flow attend only to RGB, while the paper's equation (5) is fully bidirectional. And the Stage-3 branch dropout probability is 0.05 in the scripts, not 0.1 as reported. The code is the more reliable artifact: it also shows an early exit at layer 20 inside the policy inference path and a cosine decay on the RGB-side injection to protect appearance quality. These are sensible engineering choices, but the "mutual cross-modal interaction" claim should be read as "depth and flow are strongly regularized by RGB" rather than symmetric three-way fusion.</p>

<p>Caveats. Depth and flow are pseudo-labeled with Depth-Anything 3 and DPFlow, so geometric metrics measure consistency with other estimators, not ground truth. World-model evaluation uses 50 held-out sequences; real-world policy evaluation uses 35 trials per task on one hardware platform. AEPE is computed on Middlebury color-coded flow videos in normalized RGB space, an unusual proxy. And 9 Hz effective control, while sufficient for many human-scale motions, is far below low-level servo rates, so fast contact transients remain a question.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Selecting structure, not just data</h1>

<p>Imitation learning for VLAs is hitting a data-quality ceiling: adding more demonstrations does not always help because redundancy, noise, and uneven coverage dilute the signal. This week's data-centric papers argue that the right unit of selection is neither the whole trajectory nor the individual state-action pair, but reusable behavioral subprograms — primitives and the transitions between them.</p>

