<hr/>

<h2>SIEVE: Structure-Aware Data Selection for Imitation Learning with VLA Models</h2>

<p>Wu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.06442">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.06442">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/ChangtiWu/SIEVE">Code</a></p>

<p>SIEVE's framing is clean: useful demonstrations are those that expose reusable behavioral regularities. Instead of scoring trajectories holistically or pruning state-action pairs, it discovers a vocabulary of visuo-motor primitives, represents each trajectory as a primitive composition pattern, and selects episodes that maximize coverage of primitives and the transitions between them. The method is motivated by the Minimum Description Length principle: repeating patterns should be stored in the model, not redundantly encoded in every data point.</p>

<p>Primitive discovery works in three steps. Trajectories are segmented at gripper or hand command flips, confirmed over five frames. Each segment is encoded by V-JEPA2 from eight uniformly sampled frames, reduced to 256 dimensions with PCA, and clustered with MiniBatchKMeans. The number of clusters is chosen automatically on a 10% subset by maximizing <latex>(1 - \mathcal{J}) \log \mathcal{R}</latex>, where <latex>\mathcal{J}</latex> is the median pairwise Jaccard similarity of per-trajectory cluster sets and <latex>\mathcal{R}</latex> is the median cross-trajectory cluster reuse. This favors vocabularies that are broadly reused but still structurally discriminative.</p>

<p>Each trajectory then becomes an ordered primitive sequence, its composition pattern <latex>P_i</latex>, and adjacent primitives define transitions <latex>e_i^j = (c_i^j \rightarrow c_i^{j+1})</latex>. The selection budget is allocated greedily to maximize structural exposure:</p>

<p><latex>F(\mathcal{B}) = \sum_{c \in \mathcal{C}} w_c \log(1 + n_c(\mathcal{B})) + \sum_{e \in \mathcal{E}} w_e \log(1 + n_e(\mathcal{B}))</latex></p>

<p>where <latex>w_c = q_c / |\mathcal{P}|</latex> and <latex>w_e = q_e / |\mathcal{P}|</latex> up-weight primitives and transitions that participate in many composition patterns. The log utility imposes diminishing returns, pushing selection toward broader structural coverage rather than repeatedly reinforcing the same pattern. After the budget is allocated across pattern buckets, SIEVE keeps the trajectories closest to the bucket medoid in representation space, favoring central, stable realizations for behavior cloning.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:sieve:redistribution]]</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="Greedy structural exposure allocation (from runs/2026-07-12-lamem-rynnworld-sieve/sieve/code/sieve_probe.py)"><code>def allocate_budget(patterns, transitions, weights, budget):
    B = {p: 0 for p in patterns}
    for _ in range(budget):
        best_gain, best_p = -inf, None
        for p in patterns:
            gain = marginal_log_gain(p, B, patterns, transitions, weights)
            if gain &gt; best_gain:
                best_gain, best_p = gain, p
        B[best_p] += 1
    return B</code></pre>

<p>The probe I ran on synthetic gripper-driven episodes confirms the paper's qualitative claim. Starting from a distribution dominated by a few short patterns, the greedy allocator flattens the frequency distribution and shifts the selected subset toward longer, transition-rich sequences. Pattern-frequency Gini drops from 0.463 to 0.412, and the top selected patterns become 3- and 4-primitive sequences rather than 2-primitive loops.</p>

